\pard\nowidctlpar\nooverflow\sl240\slmult1\ri360{\f0\lang1033\fs20\kerning28      
The towns all have an account set up by each Town Board in which the funds were 
a result of increasing assessments to gain more tax money to fund projects. I know
 that everyone states that taxes and assessments are not related, but in fact if
 you truly look at the information that I have provided with this letter you will
 see that they do go hand in hand. For example: the Town of Richmond would like 
to build a new Town Hall. They currently have in their account $610,000.00 that 
was accumulated over the last couple of years by collecting money from the taxpayers
. This money sits in an account waiting to be used to fund projects. They have only
 accrued enough money to fund Phase 1 of the project. \par}

\pard\nowidctlpar\nooverflow\sl240\slmult1\ri360{\f0\lang1033\fs20\kerning28      
Their plan is to raise the assessments on property owners to provide enough money
 to complete Phase 2 of the project. The taxpayers must vote on this proposal to
 decide whether this is the right way to create the funding for the project. The
 problem that we have is that if enough money is not raised to do this, then the
 town will request for a bond to pay for it. The longer the bond term, the lower
 the interest rate. Now a new problem has arisen. The town must now pay for a bond
 in which they must raise the money to pay for the bond and they will end up spending
 at least 3 times more than what they had originally planned to spend so that they
 may keep the interest rate down. It just keeps turning into a snowball effect. 
I am sure that you understand where I am going with this. \tab\par}

\pard\nowidctlpar\nooverflow\sl240\slmult1\ri360{\f0\lang1033\fs20\kerning28      
